  "prompt": "What were the major events of Spain in 1492?",
  "response": "The year 1492 was a pivotal one in Spanish history, marked by several significant events that had profound impacts on the country and the world. The major events include:\n\n1. **Completion of the Reconquista**:\n   - On January 2, 1492, the Catholic Monarchs, King Ferdinand II of Aragon and Queen Isabella I of Castile, achieved the surrender of Granada, the last Muslim stronghold in Spain. This event marked the end of the Reconquista, a centuries-long campaign to retake the Iberian Peninsula from Muslim rule.\n\n2. **Expulsion of the Jews**:\n   - On March 31, 1492, the Catholic Monarchs issued the Edict of Expulsion, known as the Alhambra Decree, which ordered the expulsion of all Jews from Spain unless they converted to Christianity. This edict led to the forced migration of tens of thousands of Jews, significantly impacting Spain's social and economic fabric.\n\n3. **Christopher Columbus's First Voyage**:\n   - On August 3, 1492, Christopher Columbus set sail from Palos de la Frontera with three ships\u2014the Santa Mar\u00eda, the Pinta, and the Ni\u00f1a\u2014under the sponsorship of the Catholic Monarchs. His voyage led to the discovery of the Americas on October 12, 1492, when he landed in the Bahamas. This event initiated widespread European exploration and colonization of the New World.\n\nThese events collectively shaped the future of Spain, establishing it as a dominant global power and significantly influencing its cultural, economic, and political landscape.",
